<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"level":1,"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(32px,4vw,48px)"}}} -->
<h1 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(32px,4vw,48px)">Native translation or AI: the difference the customer feels</h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="margin:8px 0 8px"><img src="/wp-content/themes/remarka-studio/assets/img/blog/traduzione-madrelingua-cover.svg" alt="Native translation of a website or AI: the difference in nuance, tone and culture that the customer feels" width="1200" height="630" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;border:1px solid var(--sr-bordo)"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:html -->
</section>
<!-- /wp:group -->
<!-- wp:group {"tagName":"section","className":"sr-section","layout":{"type":"constrained","contentSize":"1440px"}} -->
<section class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained sr-section"><!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch">Machine translation has come on in leaps and bounds: today understanding a text in a language you don’t know is a matter of one click, and for many uses it’s perfectly fine. Precisely for this reason the right question isn’t «AI yes or AI no», but another: for your website — the one that has to sell, convince, represent you — when does a native translation still matter? The difference is there, and the customer feels it, but it’s not where many people think. Let’s look honestly at what machine translation does well, where the hand of a native speaker really is needed, and how to choose without wasting money or ruining your reputation.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">What machine translation really does well<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">Let’s start from honesty: machine translation has improved enormously. To grasp the sense of a text, for highly standardized technical content, for enormous volumes where human review would be impossible, today it does work that ten years ago was unthinkable. Dismissing it as «always wrong» is false and helps no one. For an internal manual, a very repetitive product description, a first draft to refine, it’s a serious tool.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The point isn’t to demonize it, but to understand its limit. The machine translates the words and, ever better, the sentence too; what still escapes it is what surrounds the words: the tone, the intent, the cultural reference, the joke that works in one language and falls flat in the other. On the site that has to sell, that’s often exactly what makes the difference between a correct text and a text that convinces.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">Where the hand of a native speaker is needed<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The human nuance counts where the text has to do something beyond informing. In marketing: a slogan translated literally can come across as flat, clumsy or, in the worst cases, unintentionally comic or offensive in the target culture. In tone of voice: a site that in Italian is warm and direct can become, machine-translated, cold and impersonal — and the visitor perceives it, even without being able to say why.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">It counts, too, in local culture: idioms, units of measure, examples, references that a native speaker adapts without thinking and that the machine leaves untouched, betraying the «translated» origin of the text. It’s the difference between a site that seems written for that audience and one that seems written elsewhere and shipped there. For a tourist who books, for a buyer who chooses a supplier, that sense of «authenticity» weighs more than you’d think.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="margin:36px 0 8px"><img src="/wp-content/themes/remarka-studio/assets/img/blog/traduzione-madrelingua-schema.svg" alt="When machine translation is enough and when a native speaker is needed: technical content and volumes vs marketing, tone and culture" width="1200" height="520" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;border:1px solid var(--sr-bordo)"/><figcaption class="sr-mono" style="margin-top:12px;font-size:12.5px;letter-spacing:0.04em;color:var(--sr-grigio);max-width:75ch">Not «AI versus human», but the right text in the right place: for standardized technical content and large volumes machine translation is a serious tool; for marketing, tone of voice and cultural references — that is, the pages that have to sell and convince — the hand of a native speaker makes the difference the customer feels.</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">The most expensive mistake: machine translation left as it is<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The problem isn’t using AI to get started: it’s publishing the raw result without anyone reading it. A site with obviously automatic translations — awkward phrasing, false friends, sentences no native speaker would ever say — signals carelessness at the very moment you’re introducing yourself to a new customer. And it does so insidiously: you, who don’t speak that language, don’t notice; your customer does, on the very first line.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">There’s also a cost you don’t see: lost trust doesn’t come back. A visitor who perceives a «badly translated» site doubts the rest — the seriousness, the quality, the security of payments. In doubt, they close the tab. That’s why a text meant to represent you abroad should at least be read and fixed by a native speaker: not out of snobbery, but because that’s where it’s decided whether they choose you.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="/en/tools/does-it-sound-native/">Try for free how your text «sounds» to a native speaker →</a></p><p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="/en/blog/localization-roi/">Read also: the ROI of localization, how much translating really pays →</a></p>
<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">How to choose, without wasting or risking<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The practical choice isn’t all-or-nothing. A sensible approach is by tiers: low-stakes, high-volume content — very technical listings, archives, documentation — can start from a good machine translation; the pages that sell and convince — home, services, landing pages, stories — deserve a native translation or review. That way you spend where it pays and save where it doesn’t, without putting at risk the face you show the market.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">It’s the approach we work with on multilingual sites: technology where it helps, the hand of a native speaker where it counts. We don’t translate with a plugin and be done with it; the languages of your customers we write so they sound native, with correct hreflang and international SEO. Because a site in another language mustn’t just be understood: it has to convince someone to choose you.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
